'''''Lina Fisser''''' was a 1,497 GRT [[cargo ship]] that was built in 1912 by [[Blyth Shipbuilding Company|Blyth Shipbuilding and Drydock Co Ltd]], [[Blyth, Northumberland|Blyth]] as '''''Thyra Menier''''' for British owners. In 1918, she was sold to [[Belgium|Belgian]] owners and renamed '''''Luis Pindal'''''. In 1925, she was sold to [[Italy|Italian]] owners and renamed '''''Bellini'''''. A further sale in 1928 to [[Germany|German]] owners saw her renamed '''''Bollan''''' and then ''Lina Fisser'' in 1936.

She was seized by the Allies in May 1945 at [[Keil]], Germany and passed to the [[Ministry of War Transport]] (MoWT) and renamed '''''Empire Conderton'''''. In 1947, she was sold into merchant service and was renamed '''''Marchmont'''''. In 1952, a further sale saw her renamed '''''Irene M'''''. In 1955, she was sold to Canada, serving until 1957 when she was scrapped.

==Description==
The ship was built in 1912 by Blyth Shipbuilding and Drydock Co Ltd, Blyth.<ref name=Ships>{{cite book | first = and Sawyer, L A| last = Mitchell, W H | year = 1995| month = | title = The Empire Ships| pages = | publisher = Lloyd's of London Press Ltd| location = London, New York, Hamburg, Hong Kong|isbn=1-85044-275-4}}</ref> She was completed in September 1912.<ref name=Bollan30>{{cite web|url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=30b0160.pdf |title=LLOYD'S REGISTER, NAVIRES A VAPEUER ET A MOTEURS |publisher=Plimsoll Ship Data |accessdate=3 June 2010}}</ref>

The ship was {{convert|238|ft|8|in|m|2}} long, with a beam of {{convert|36|ft|1|in|m|2}} a depth of {{convert|20|ft|0|in|m|2}}.<ref name=Bollan30/> Her draught was approximately {{convert|16|ft|1|in|m|2}}<ref name=Conderton45/> She had a GRT of 1,497 and a NRT of 838,<ref name=Bollan30/>

The ship was propelled by a [[triple expansion steam engine]], which had two cylinders of 17{{frac|3|16}} inches (44 cm), {{convert|28|in|cm}} and {{convert|46|in|cm}}  diameter by {{convert|33|in|cm}}  stroke. The engine was built by G T Grey, [[South Shields]].<ref name=Bollan30/>

==History==
''Thyra Menier'' was built for the Donald Steamship Company, [[Bristol]].<ref name=Mariners>{{cite web|url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/EmpireC.html |title=Empire - C |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=4 June 2010}}</ref> The United Kingdom Official Number 127100 was allocatd.<ref name=ON>{{cite web|url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/ON120000.htm|title=ON120000 |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=4 June 2010}}</ref> In 1915, she was under [[bareboat charter|charter]] to [[Menier Chocolate|Henri Menier]] and had been sub-chartered to the Canadian-American Steamship Corporation, [[New York City|New York]]. The [[Admiralty]] requisitioned her, but her charterers objects, claiming that the requisition could not take place as the ship was not in British waters. At the time, the ship was in [[dry dock]] in New York.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |title=A new question in Admiralty Law |first= |last= |newspaper=New York Times |page=p19 |date=23 June 1915 |accessdate=4 June 2010 |url=http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?_r=1&res=9B03E4DC1038E633A25750C2A9609C946496D6CF }}</ref>

In 1918, ''Thyra Menier'' was sold to F Lecoeuvre, Belgium and renamed ''Luis Pidal''. She served until 1925 when she was sold to Puglisi & Tomasini, Italy and was renamed ''Bellini''.<ref name=Ships/> In 1928, she was sold to August Bolten, Germany and was renamed ''Bollan''.<ref name=Ships/> Her port of registry was [[Hamburg]] and the [[Code Letters]] RHCT were allocated.<ref name=Bollan30/> In 1934, her code letters were changed to DHCR.<ref name=Bollan34>{{cite web|url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=34b0120.pdf |title=LLOYD'S REGISTER, STEAMERS & MOTORSHIPS |publisher=Plimsoll Ship Data |accessdate=4 June 2010}}</ref> In 1936,<ref name=Ships/> ''Bollan'' was sold to Reunert & Co GmbH. She was placed under the management of Fisser & Van Doornum, [[Emden]] and was renamed ''Lina Fisser''.<ref name=Fisser36>{{cite web|url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=37b0527.pdf |title=LLOYD'S REGISTER, NAVIRES A VAPEUER ET A MOTEURS |publisher=Plimsoll Ship Data |accessdate=4 June 2010}}</ref>

''Lina Fisser'' was seized by the Allies in May 1945 at [[Kiel]], passed to the MoWT and renamed ''Empire Conderton''.<ref name=Ships/> Her port of registry was changed to [[London]] and the Code Letters GMWD were allocated. She regained her Official Number 127100. She was placed under the management of the Alliance Marine Transport Co Ltd. ''Empire Conderton'' was recorded as 1,558 GRT, 847 NRT.<ref name=Conderton45>{{cite web|url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=45a1188.pdf |title=LLOYD'S REGISTER, STEAMERS & MOTORSHIPS |publisher=Plimsoll Ship Data |accessdate=4 June 2010}}</ref> In 1947, she was sold to J P Hadoulis Ltd, London and renamed ''Marchmont''. In 1952, she was sold to A Moschakis, London and renamed ''Irene M''.  She was sold in 1955 to Tampa Shipping Ltd, [[Nova Scotia]]. ''Irene M'' was sold in 1957 to Marine Industries Ltd, [[Montreal]]. She was scrapped later that year at [[Sorel-Tracy, Quebec|Sorel]], [[Quebec]].<ref name=Ships/>

